I think an ideal student life should be one where there is lesser emphasis on grades and academics. I learnt a great deal when I went on exchange because the grades given out are absolute, you are not graded one grade down just because you failed to get 87/100 and your 85/100 is not worthy of a B in the eyes of the system. The emphasis on grades and the bell curve system in University takes away the fun in learning I experienced on exchange. Since everyone gets an absolute score, the students are always ready to help one another out, discussions are less brutal about who is right and who is wrong but how we can all learn together. Overall, my life in University has only been made a little better through the different non-academic experiences I have been through. Would I recommend someone to study in University or head overseas? Definitely head overseas, I feel like right now, "ideal student life" is far from what we currently have.

I hope it becomes less challenging in terms of academic life. I feel that for my course academics are ideally manageable, but when group work comes into play sometimes there are instances where one has to put in alot more hard work than someone else to bring a piece of work up to standard, without recognition nor reward, especially when the end grade is the same. This is rather unsettling, because this requires additional time on the part of the student which cannot be used for him or her to invest in other areas of growth that can help enhance his or her resume which could be very unfair. This is especially because academics are usually judged by CAP only, and leadership in these academic projects is generally not considered actual leadership in the eyes of employers. For top industries like consulting and investment banking where CAP is the first screening criteria, this can be a source of unfairness. Working on addressing this unfairness will go a long way to recognizing students and their hard work, rather than rewarding what appears to be highly individualistic and selfish behaviour which comes with a common score in group projects. This will allow all students to have an opportunity to pursue student life endeavours rather than be held back from enjoying student life activities by having to put in additional time and effort performing academic work for others who fall short of doing so.

An ideal student life is one where the academics focus more on genuinely getting students to learn and grow, instead of worrying and sabotaging one another to "beat the bell curve". At the same time, it is to play hard and engage in activities/causes that I am genuinely passionate about. I think that there is a common assumption that having fun in university means being very social in all the hall/camp/large-scale events, but those do not always work for everyone. Some people may be more introverted but equally passionate and happy pursuing their interests. I think an ideal student life, for me, is one where we respect that others may not have the same interests as us, and there should not be a benchmark for the "best" student life a student has to strive for. A student life should be balanced, and that balance is one that makes the student happy and fulfilled.
